06105nam a22007695i 9781845459994DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97818454599947 a10.1515/97818454599942doi  a(DE-B1597)637197  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a306.8740943090400aRaising Citizens in the 'Century of the Child' :bThe United States and German Central Europe in Comparative Perspective /ced. by Dirk Schumann. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German History ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tIntroduction CHILD-REARING AND CITIZENSHIP IN THE TWENTIETH CENTURY -- tPart I FOUNDATIONS -- tChapter 1 CHILDREN AND THE NATIONAL INTEREST -- tPart II NEW BEGINNINGS -- tChapter 2 CHILDREN’S FUTURE, NATION’S FUTURE Race, Citizenship, and the United States Children’s Bureau -- tChapter 3 FROM REFORM PEDAGOGY TO WAR PEDAGOGY Education Reform before 1914 and the Mobilization for War in Germany -- tChapter 4 “LINKED WITH THE WELFARE OF ALL PEOPLES” The American Kindergarten, Americanization, and Internationalism in the First World War -- tPart III PARENTAL RIGHTS AND STATE DEMANDS -- tChapter 5 HOW SHOULD WE RAISE OUR SON BENJAMIN? Advice Literature for Mothers in Early Twentieth-Century Germany -- tChapter 6 DEBUNKING MOTHER LOVE American Mothers and the Momism Critique in the Mid Twentieth Century -- tChapter 7 FATHERHOOD, RECHRISTIANIZATION, AND THE QUEST FOR DEMOCRACY IN POSTWAR WEST GERMANY -- tPart IV PARENTAL RIGHTS AND STATE DEMANDS -- tChapter 8 WHO OWNS CHILDREN? Parents, Children, and the State in the United States South -- tChapter 9 “CHILDREN BETRAY THEIR FATHER AND MOTHER” Collective Education, Nationalism, and Democracy in the Bohemian Lands, 1900–1948 -- tChapter 10 ASSERTING THEIR “NATURAL RIGHT” Parents and Public Schooling in Post-1945 Germany -- tChapter 11 “SPECIAL RELATIONSHIPS” The State, Social Workers, and Abused Children in the United States, 1950–1990 -- tSELECT BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 20th century, declared at its start to be the “Century of the Child” by Swedish author Ellen Key, saw an unprecedented expansion of state activity in and expert knowledge on child-rearing on both sides of the Atlantic. Children were seen as a crucial national resource whose care could not be left to families alone. However, the exact scope and degree of state intervention and expert influence as well as the rights and roles of mothers and fathers remained subjects of heated debates throughout the century. While there is a growing scholarly interest in the history of childhood, research in the field remains focused on national narratives. This volume compares the impact of state intervention and expert influence on theories and practices of raising children in the U.S. and German Central Europe. In particular, the contributors focus on institutions such as kindergartens and schools where the private and the public spheres intersected, on notions of “race” and “ethnicity,” “normality” and “deviance,” and on the impact of wars and changes in political regimes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh1 aBerg, Ellen L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBullard, Katharine S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurry, Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonson, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsrael, Charles A., econt